-- ============================================
-- BOOK STUDIES - New Testament Letters
-- ============================================

-- 1 Corinthians 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The city of Corinth was a major commercial hub in ancient Greece, known for its wealth, diversity, and moral corruption. The temple of Aphrodite on the Acrocorinth employed over 1,000 temple prostitutes. Paul founded this church around AD 50-51 during his second missionary journey, spending 18 months there.

The Corinthian church struggled with divisions, immorality, lawsuits among believers, and confusion about spiritual gifts. Paul wrote this letter around AD 55 from Ephesus to address these issues. Despite their problems, Paul still called them "sanctified in Christ Jesus" (1:2), showing that our standing in Christ isn''t based on our perfection.

This letter gives us the most detailed picture of early church life, including their worship practices, the Lord''s Supper, spiritual gifts, and the resurrection. Paul''s famous "love chapter" (chapter 13) was written to correct their misuse of spiritual gifts.'
WHERE slug = '1-corinthians-14-days';

-- 1 John 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The apostle John wrote this letter late in his life, likely around AD 85-95, making him the last surviving apostle. He was writing to combat early forms of Gnosticism—a heresy teaching that matter was evil and therefore Jesus couldn''t have come in a real human body.

John knew Jesus intimately—he reclined next to Jesus at the Last Supper, stood at the foot of the cross, and was the first apostle to believe at the empty tomb. His letter reflects this intimate knowledge, repeatedly emphasizing what "we have heard, seen, looked at, and touched" (1:1).

The letter contains no formal greeting or named recipients, suggesting it was a circular letter for multiple churches in Asia Minor. John''s purpose was clear: "I write these things to you who believe in the name of the Son of God so that you may know that you have eternal life" (5:13). This letter provides assurance of salvation through three tests: doctrinal (believing Jesus is God come in flesh), moral (obedience), and social (love for other believers).'
WHERE slug = '1-john-7-days';

-- 1 Peter 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Peter wrote this letter around AD 62-64, shortly before Nero''s persecution intensified against Christians in Rome. He wrote from "Babylon" (5:13), likely a code name for Rome, with the help of Silas (Silvanus) as his secretary.

The recipients were scattered Christians in five Roman provinces of Asia Minor (modern Turkey). Peter calls them "elect exiles" or "strangers"—emphasizing their dual identity as chosen by God but living as foreigners in a hostile world. Many were likely Gentile converts facing social ostracism for abandoning their former way of life.

Peter''s transformation is evident throughout this letter. The impulsive fisherman who denied Jesus three times now writes with pastoral maturity about suffering for Christ. He draws heavily on his personal memories: the transfiguration (5:1), Jesus'' teaching about shepherding (5:2-4), and Christ''s silent suffering before accusers (2:23). His theme is hope—the "living hope" that sustains believers through trials.'
WHERE slug = '1-peter-7-days';

-- Acts 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Book of Acts is the second volume of Luke''s historical work, picking up where his Gospel ended. Written around AD 62, it covers approximately 30 years of church history from Jesus'' ascension (AD 30) to Paul''s imprisonment in Rome (AD 60-62).

Luke was a physician and Paul''s traveling companion. His "we" passages (16:10-17; 20:5-21:18; 27:1-28:16) indicate he was an eyewitness to many events. He interviewed other eyewitnesses, including possibly Mary the mother of Jesus, for his careful historical research.

Acts serves as the bridge between the Gospels and the Epistles, showing how the church emerged from a small group of disciples in Jerusalem to a movement spanning the Roman Empire. The book traces the gospel''s expansion in widening circles: Jerusalem, Judea, Samaria, and the ends of the earth—exactly as Jesus predicted in 1:8. This geographical and ethnic expansion demonstrates how the gospel broke through every barrier: Jewish/Gentile, slave/free, male/female.'
WHERE slug = 'acts-14-days';

-- Colossians 5 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Paul wrote Colossians around AD 60-62 while imprisoned in Rome. Interestingly, Paul had never visited Colossae—the church was founded by Epaphras, likely one of Paul''s converts from his ministry in Ephesus (about 100 miles away).

Colossae was a small city in the Lycus Valley of Asia Minor, overshadowed by nearby Laodicea and Hierapolis. The church faced a unique heresy combining Jewish legalism (circumcision, dietary laws, festivals) with early Gnostic ideas (worship of angels, secret knowledge, harsh treatment of the body).

Paul''s response was not to attack the heresy directly but to present the supremacy and sufficiency of Christ. The letter contains one of the most exalted Christological passages in Scripture (1:15-20), emphasizing that Jesus is the image of the invisible God, creator of all things, and head of the church. In Christ "all the fullness of the Deity lives in bodily form" (2:9)—making any addition to Christ unnecessary and insulting.'
WHERE slug = 'colossians-5-days';

-- Ephesians 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Ephesians was written by Paul around AD 60-62 during his first Roman imprisonment. Unlike most of Paul''s letters, Ephesians doesn''t address specific problems. Instead, it''s a majestic presentation of God''s eternal purpose in Christ.

Ephesus was one of the largest cities in the Roman Empire (population ~250,000), home to the temple of Artemis—one of the Seven Wonders of the ancient world. Paul spent about three years there, and a riot by silversmiths shows how the gospel impacted local economy (Acts 19).

Some early manuscripts lack "in Ephesus" in verse 1, suggesting this may have been a circular letter for multiple churches. The letter divides neatly in half: chapters 1-3 are theological (what God has done), chapters 4-6 are practical (how we should live). Paul emphasizes that believers are no longer strangers but fellow citizens, members of God''s household, built on the foundation of apostles and prophets with Christ as the cornerstone.'
WHERE slug = 'ephesians-7-days';

-- Galatians 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Galatians is Paul''s most passionate and personal letter, written around AD 48-49, making it possibly his earliest epistle. He wrote with unusual urgency: "I am astonished that you are so quickly deserting the one who called you" (1:6).

The "Galatians" were believers in the Roman province of Galatia (central modern Turkey). After Paul established these churches on his first missionary journey, false teachers arrived teaching that Gentiles must be circumcised and follow Jewish law to be fully saved. This wasn''t adding to the gospel—it was destroying it.

Martin Luther called Galatians "my epistle" and his commentary on it helped spark the Protestant Reformation. Paul''s argument is straightforward: justification comes through faith in Christ alone, not works of the law. He uses Abraham as his example—justified by faith 430 years before the law existed. The law was a guardian until Christ came, but now believers are adult sons and heirs, not slaves. Freedom, not legalism, marks the authentic Christian life.'
WHERE slug = 'galatians-7-days';

-- Hebrews 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Hebrews is one of the New Testament''s most mysterious books—we don''t know who wrote it, when exactly it was written, or to whom precisely it was addressed. What we do know is its message: Jesus is better.

The recipients were Jewish Christians facing pressure to return to Judaism. The temple still stood (suggesting a date before AD 70), and Judaism was a legal religion in Rome while Christianity was not. The temptation to retreat was real.

The author systematically demonstrates Christ''s superiority: better than angels (chapters 1-2), better than Moses (3-4), a better priesthood than Aaron''s (5-7), a better covenant (8-10), and faith that endures (11-13). The book contains five warning passages about the danger of falling away, balanced with rich assurances of Christ''s sufficient work. The famous "faith chapter" (Hebrews 11) provides a gallery of Old Testament heroes who persevered, encouraging readers to "run with endurance the race marked out for us, fixing our eyes on Jesus" (12:1-2).'
WHERE slug = 'hebrews-14-days';

-- James 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'James, the half-brother of Jesus, wrote this letter—likely the earliest New Testament book (around AD 45-48). James didn''t believe in Jesus during His earthly ministry (John 7:5), but the risen Christ appeared to him personally (1 Corinthians 15:7), transforming him into a pillar of the Jerusalem church.

James wrote to "the twelve tribes scattered among the nations"—Jewish Christians dispersed throughout the Roman Empire. His letter is intensely practical, often compared to Old Testament wisdom literature. It contains 54 commands in just 108 verses, covering topics like trials, temptation, favoritism, faith and works, the tongue, worldliness, and prayer.

The relationship between James and Paul on "faith and works" has puzzled many. But they''re addressing different problems: Paul combats legalism (adding works to faith for salvation), while James confronts a dead "faith" that produces no works. As James says, "Faith without deeds is dead" (2:26). True saving faith inevitably produces fruit. James doesn''t contradict Paul—he complements him.'
WHERE slug = 'james-7-days';

-- John 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'John''s Gospel was written last, around AD 85-95, after the other three Gospels had circulated for decades. John, the "beloved disciple," wrote as an eyewitness who had intimate access to Jesus—he was part of the inner three (with Peter and James) and reclined next to Jesus at the Last Supper.

John''s purpose is explicitly stated: "These are written that you may believe that Jesus is the Messiah, the Son of God, and that by believing you may have life in his name" (20:31). Unlike the Synoptics (Matthew, Mark, Luke), John is highly selective, focusing on seven miraculous signs and seven "I AM" statements that reveal Jesus'' identity.

About 90% of John''s content is unique—including key events like the wedding at Cana, Nicodemus, the woman at the well, raising of Lazarus, and Jesus washing the disciples'' feet. John assumes his readers know the Synoptic accounts and provides a complementary theological interpretation. His prologue (1:1-18) establishes Jesus as the eternal Word (Logos) who was with God and was God, now made flesh.'
WHERE slug = 'john-21-days';

-- Luke 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Luke was a Gentile physician and companion of Paul—the only non-Jewish author of a New Testament book. He wrote this Gospel around AD 60-62 to "Theophilus" (possibly a Roman official or patron whose name means "lover of God"), presenting Christianity as a legitimate faith for the Greco-Roman world.

Luke emphasizes his careful research: "I myself have carefully investigated everything from the beginning" (1:3). He likely interviewed Mary, the mother of Jesus, explaining why only Luke records the annunciation, Elizabeth''s greeting, and Mary''s Magnificat. His Gospel contains the most detailed account of Jesus'' birth and the only record of Jesus at age 12.

Luke uniquely emphasizes Jesus'' concern for outsiders: women, Samaritans, tax collectors, the poor, and Gentiles. His parables of the Good Samaritan, the Prodigal Son, and the Rich Man and Lazarus appear only here. Luke also highlights prayer (recording nine occasions of Jesus praying) and the Holy Spirit (mentioned more than in Matthew and Mark combined). His Gospel begins and ends in the temple, showing continuity with Israel''s faith.'
WHERE slug = 'luke-21-days';

-- Mark 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Mark wrote the earliest Gospel, around AD 55-65, likely in Rome for Gentile readers. Church tradition uniformly identifies Mark as Peter''s interpreter, recording Peter''s eyewitness preaching about Jesus. This explains the Gospel''s vivid details and focus on what Jesus did rather than lengthy teaching sections.

Mark moves fast. His favorite word is "immediately" (used about 40 times). The Gospel emphasizes Jesus as the Suffering Servant—half the book covers the final week of Jesus'' life. There''s no birth narrative; Mark begins with John the Baptist and Jesus'' baptism, immediately plunging into Jesus'' public ministry.

Mark presents Jesus as a man of action: healing, casting out demons, confronting religious leaders, and ultimately going to the cross. The central question is Peter''s confession at Caesarea Philippi: "You are the Messiah" (8:29). But Jesus immediately redefines messiahship in terms of suffering and death. The Gospel''s original ending (16:8) is abrupt, leaving readers with the empty tomb and fearful women—perhaps intentionally provocative, asking readers: "What will you do with the risen Jesus?"'
WHERE slug = 'mark-14-days';

-- Philippians 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Paul wrote to the Philippians around AD 60-62 from prison in Rome—yet this is his most joy-filled letter. The words "joy" and "rejoice" appear 16 times in just four chapters. Paul demonstrates that circumstances don''t determine contentment; Christ does.

Philippi was a Roman colony in Macedonia (northern Greece), named after Philip II of Macedon (Alexander the Great''s father). Paul founded this church on his second missionary journey around AD 49-50, and it was the first church established in Europe. The church began with three diverse converts: Lydia (wealthy businesswoman), a demon-possessed slave girl, and a Roman jailer.

The Philippians had a special relationship with Paul—they were the only church from whom he accepted financial support. Now they''ve sent Epaphroditus with another gift for Paul in prison. Paul writes to thank them, update them on his situation, and encourage unity. The letter contains the magnificent "Christ hymn" (2:5-11), one of the earliest Christian confessions about Jesus'' incarnation, death, and exaltation.'
WHERE slug = 'philippians-7-days';

-- Romans Deep Dive
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Romans is Paul''s masterpiece—his most systematic and comprehensive presentation of the gospel. Written around AD 57 from Corinth, it''s addressed to a church Paul didn''t found and hadn''t yet visited, explaining why it reads more like a theological treatise than a typical letter.

The Roman church likely began when Jews who had been in Jerusalem at Pentecost (Acts 2:10) returned home with the gospel. The church had become predominantly Gentile after Emperor Claudius expelled Jews from Rome in AD 49. By the time Paul wrote, Jews were returning, creating tensions between Jewish and Gentile believers.

Paul addresses this tension with his gospel: all—Jew and Gentile alike—are under sin and justified only by faith in Christ. He traces salvation from condemnation (1-3) through justification (3-5) to sanctification (6-8), then addresses Israel''s place in God''s plan (9-11), and finally applies the gospel to daily living (12-16). The theme verse is 1:16-17: "For I am not ashamed of the gospel, because it is the power of God that brings salvation to everyone who believes."'
WHERE slug = 'romans-deep-dive';

-- Revelation 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The apostle John wrote Revelation around AD 95 during his exile on the island of Patmos under Emperor Domitian''s persecution. It''s the only New Testament book that promises blessing to those who read it aloud, hear it, and take it to heart (1:3).

Revelation is apocalyptic literature—a genre familiar to first-century readers but often misunderstood today. It uses symbolic imagery to communicate spiritual truths, drawing heavily from Daniel, Ezekiel, and Zechariah. The number 7 appears 54 times (7 churches, 7 seals, 7 trumpets, 7 bowls), symbolizing completeness.

The book is addressed to seven real churches in Asia Minor (modern Turkey), each facing unique challenges. But its ultimate message transcends time: God is sovereign over history, Christ will return victorious, evil will be judged, and God''s people will dwell with Him forever in a new creation. Though filled with dramatic imagery of judgment, Revelation ends not with destruction but with restoration—the marriage supper of the Lamb and the New Jerusalem where God dwells with His people.'
WHERE slug = 'revelation-21-days';

-- Revelation Without Fear
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Many Christians avoid Revelation because it seems confusing or frightening. But it''s the only biblical book that explicitly promises blessing to its readers (1:3). The word "revelation" (Greek: apokalypsis) means "unveiling"—God pulling back the curtain to show spiritual realities.

First-century Christians facing persecution found comfort here. When Rome seemed all-powerful, Revelation revealed the true King on the throne. When emperor worship was demanded, believers saw that Jesus alone is "Lord of lords and King of kings" (17:14). The book''s terrifying imagery of judgment wasn''t meant to frighten believers but to assure them that evil wouldn''t have the last word.

Revelation uses symbols from the Old Testament that would have been familiar to Jewish Christians. The lion and lamb imagery, the number 666 (falling short of the perfect 777), the streets of gold and gates of pearl—all convey theological truths. Read properly, Revelation isn''t a puzzle to solve but a promise to embrace: Jesus wins, death loses, and those who persevere will reign with Christ forever.'
WHERE slug = 'revelation-without-fear';

-- ============================================
-- BOOK STUDIES - Old Testament
-- ============================================

-- Daniel 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Daniel was a teenager when Babylon conquered Jerusalem in 605 BC, carrying away the royal family and nobility. For nearly 70 years, he served in the courts of four successive rulers: Nebuchadnezzar, Belshazzar, Darius the Mede, and Cyrus of Persia.

The book divides into two sections: chapters 1-6 contain historical narratives (the fiery furnace, lions'' den, writing on the wall), while chapters 7-12 record apocalyptic visions. Daniel and his friends model faithful living in a pagan culture without compromise—they ate vegetables rather than defile themselves with the king''s food, yet served with excellence and gained influence.

Daniel''s prophecies are remarkably precise. His vision of four kingdoms (chapters 2 and 7) traces world history from Babylon through Medo-Persia, Greece, and Rome. His "seventy weeks" prophecy (chapter 9) predicts the timing of Messiah''s coming. Jesus called Daniel "the prophet" (Matthew 24:15) and drew heavily from Daniel''s "Son of Man" imagery. The book assures us that God is sovereign over nations and history—a comforting truth when earthly kingdoms seem all-powerful.'
WHERE slug = 'daniel-14-days';

-- Exodus 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Exodus ("going out") is the foundational story of Israel''s redemption. Over 400 years after Joseph brought his family to Egypt, the Israelites had grown into a nation of perhaps 2 million people—and were enslaved by a Pharaoh "who did not know Joseph" (1:8).

The book covers roughly 80 years but focuses on three key events: the deliverance from Egypt (chapters 1-18), the giving of the Law at Sinai (19-24), and the building of the tabernacle (25-40). Each reveals God''s character: He is a rescuing God who hears His people''s cries, a holy God who sets standards for His people, and a present God who dwells among them.

The Passover lamb, whose blood protected Israelite homes from the death angel, becomes the defining image of redemption. The New Testament explicitly connects it to Christ: "For Christ, our Passover lamb, has been sacrificed" (1 Corinthians 5:7). When Jesus instituted the Lord''s Supper at a Passover meal, He was declaring Himself the ultimate Passover Lamb whose blood brings deliverance from sin and death.'
WHERE slug = 'exodus-21-days';

-- Genesis 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Genesis ("beginning") answers life''s biggest questions: Where did everything come from? Why are we here? What went wrong with the world? Is there hope? Written by Moses during Israel''s wilderness wandering, it covers more time than any other biblical book—from creation to Joseph''s death (roughly 2,300 years).

The book divides naturally: chapters 1-11 cover primeval history (creation, fall, flood, Babel), while chapters 12-50 focus on patriarchal history (Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Joseph). Genesis 3 is the Bible''s hinge—explaining how God''s good creation became corrupted by sin and why humanity needs a Savior.

The theme of blessing and curse runs throughout. God created a blessed world, but sin brought curse. Yet even in pronouncing judgment on the serpent, God promised that the woman''s "seed" would crush the serpent''s head (3:15)—the first gospel announcement. Through Abraham, God began His plan to bless all nations. The patriarchs'' stories show God faithfully working through flawed people to accomplish His purposes.'
WHERE slug = 'genesis-21-days';

-- Isaiah 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Isaiah prophesied for about 60 years (roughly 740-680 BC) during one of Judah''s most turbulent periods. He served under four kings and witnessed the northern kingdom of Israel fall to Assyria in 722 BC. His name means "Yahweh is salvation"—perfectly capturing his message.

The book divides into two major sections: chapters 1-39 focus on judgment (with Assyria as the threat), while chapters 40-66 offer comfort (looking beyond to Babylon and ultimate restoration). Isaiah is sometimes called the "fifth Gospel" because of its detailed Messianic prophecies—the virgin birth (7:14), the child called "Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God" (9:6), and the Suffering Servant who bears our iniquities (chapter 53).

Isaiah''s vision of God''s holiness (chapter 6) shaped his ministry. The thrice-holy God who fills heaven and earth called Isaiah to proclaim judgment to a deaf and blind people—yet promised a remnant would survive and from Jesse''s stump a Branch would emerge. New Testament writers quote Isaiah more than any other Old Testament prophet, seeing Jesus as the fulfillment of its hopes.'
WHERE slug = 'isaiah-21-days';

-- Jeremiah 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jeremiah prophesied for about 40 years (627-586 BC) during Judah''s final decline and fall to Babylon. Called as a young man, he was forbidden to marry—his solitary life symbolizing Judah''s coming devastation. He''s known as the "weeping prophet" because of his deep grief over his people''s fate.

Jeremiah''s message was unpopular: surrender to Babylon. This seemed like treason, and he was beaten, imprisoned, thrown into a cistern, and publicly humiliated. Yet he faithfully delivered God''s message of judgment, calling for repentance that never came. He watched Jerusalem burn and most of its people killed or exiled.

Despite the overwhelming judgment, Jeremiah proclaimed hope. His "new covenant" prophecy (31:31-34) is the longest Old Testament passage quoted in the New Testament (Hebrews 8). God would make a covenant written on hearts, not tablets—where all would know Him and sins would be remembered no more. This finds fulfillment in Christ. Jeremiah shows us that faithfulness isn''t measured by success but by obedience.'
WHERE slug = 'jeremiah-21-days';

-- Psalms Favorites 30
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Psalms (Hebrew: "Tehillim," meaning "praises") is Israel''s inspired songbook and prayer book—150 poems spanning roughly 1,000 years of composition. David wrote about half, but other authors include Moses (Psalm 90), Solomon, Asaph, and the sons of Korah.

The Psalms cover the full range of human emotion: exuberant praise (Psalm 150), deep despair (Psalm 88), righteous anger (Psalm 137), quiet trust (Psalm 23), honest doubt (Psalm 73), and passionate love for God (Psalm 63). They teach us how to pray by giving us words when we have none.

Jesus quoted the Psalms more than any other book. He sang them at the Last Supper (the Hallel psalms, 113-118), cried out Psalm 22 from the cross, and explained that the Psalms spoke about Him (Luke 24:44). Early Christians continued singing psalms (Colossians 3:16), and the Psalter has remained central to Christian worship for 2,000 years. These ancient songs still give voice to our deepest experiences with God.'
WHERE slug = 'psalms-favorites-30';

-- Proverbs and Psalms 31
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'This plan pairs two of the most beloved Old Testament books for daily wisdom and worship. Psalms teach us how to pray and relate to God emotionally; Proverbs teach us how to live skillfully and wisely in everyday situations.

Proverbs is practical wisdom literature, primarily from Solomon, who composed 3,000 proverbs (1 Kings 4:32). Written to train young men for adult responsibility, its principles apply universally. Proverbs isn''t about earning salvation but living well—skill in the art of godly living. Its statements are general principles, not absolute promises; they describe how life typically works, not guarantees.

Reading Psalms and Proverbs together creates a balanced spiritual diet: vertical relationship with God and horizontal relationships with others, emotional expression and practical wisdom, worship and work. Many Christians read one chapter of Proverbs daily (matching the 31 chapters to the days of the month) alongside five Psalms—completing both books each month. This rhythm shapes character over time.'
WHERE slug = 'psalms-proverbs-31';

-- ============================================
-- CHARACTER STUDIES
-- ============================================

-- Life of Abraham 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Abraham (originally Abram) was born around 2166 BC in Ur of the Chaldees, a sophisticated city in modern-day Iraq. God called him to leave everything familiar at age 75 and journey to an unknown land. This "friend of God" (James 2:23) became the father of three major world religions: Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.

Abraham''s life was marked by faith—and failure. He believed God''s promise of countless descendants despite having no children. He offered hospitality to angels and interceded for Sodom. Yet he also lied about Sarah being his sister (twice), fathered Ishmael through Sarah''s servant Hagar, and laughed at God''s promise of a son in old age.

The ultimate test came when God asked Abraham to sacrifice Isaac—the long-awaited son of promise. Abraham''s willingness to obey, trusting that God could raise the dead (Hebrews 11:19), demonstrated the faith that made him righteous before God. The New Testament calls him the "father of all who believe" (Romans 4:11), showing that right standing with God always comes through faith, not works.'
WHERE slug = 'life-of-abraham-14';

-- Life of David 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'David was Israel''s greatest king, ruling approximately 1010-970 BC. His story spans more biblical chapters than any other individual except Jesus. He''s mentioned over 1,000 times in Scripture, and Jesus Himself is called the "Son of David."

David was the youngest of Jesse''s eight sons, tending sheep in Bethlehem when Samuel anointed him as Israel''s next king. He rose to prominence by killing Goliath, earned Saul''s jealous hatred, lived as a fugitive, and eventually united all twelve tribes. Under his reign, Israel reached its greatest territorial extent.

Yet David''s life also includes devastating failures—adultery with Bathsheba, murder of Uriah, and poor parenting that led to Absalom''s rebellion. What made David "a man after God''s own heart" (Acts 13:22) wasn''t moral perfection but his response to sin: genuine repentance (Psalm 51). David teaches us that God can use broken people for great purposes, and that the measure of a person isn''t found in never falling but in how they respond when they do.'
WHERE slug = 'life-of-david-14';

-- Life of Joseph 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Joseph was Jacob''s eleventh son, born to Rachel after years of barrenness. His story (Genesis 37-50) is one of the longest continuous narratives in the Bible and one of its most carefully crafted. No sins are recorded of Joseph—not because he was sinless, but because the narrative focuses on God''s providential work through suffering.

Joseph''s life follows a dramatic arc: favored son, sold into slavery by jealous brothers, successful servant in Potiphar''s house, falsely accused and imprisoned, and finally exalted to second-in-command of Egypt. Each setback positioned him for greater influence. What his brothers intended for evil, God used for good "to accomplish what is now being done, the saving of many lives" (50:20).

Joseph is one of the clearest Old Testament "types" of Christ: beloved son, rejected by his own, suffering unjustly, exalted to a place of authority, and becoming the source of salvation for those who rejected him. His story reassures us that God can weave even betrayal, injustice, and suffering into His redemptive purposes.'
WHERE slug = 'life-of-joseph-14';

-- Life of Moses 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Moses is the most prominent human figure in the Old Testament, mentioned in every section of both Testaments. He led Israel''s exodus from Egypt, received the Law at Sinai, and guided the people for 40 years in the wilderness. He''s called the greatest prophet until Christ (Deuteronomy 34:10).

Moses'' life divides into three 40-year periods: as an Egyptian prince (Acts 7:23), as a shepherd in Midian after killing an Egyptian, and as Israel''s leader after the burning bush encounter. His story shows that God often prepares leaders through wilderness seasons.

Moses'' relationship with God was uniquely intimate—God spoke with him "face to face, as one speaks to a friend" (Exodus 33:11). Yet Moses also had significant failures: he murdered an Egyptian, made excuses at the burning bush, and struck the rock in anger rather than speaking to it, forfeiting entry to the Promised Land. Like David, Moses shows that God uses imperfect people and that leadership doesn''t exempt one from consequences.'
WHERE slug = 'life-of-moses-21';

-- Life of Paul 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Paul (originally Saul) is arguably the most influential Christian after Jesus. Born a Roman citizen in Tarsus, trained as a Pharisee under Gamaliel, he initially persecuted Christians with murderous zeal. His dramatic conversion on the Damascus Road (around AD 33-35) transformed him into the apostle to the Gentiles.

Paul planted churches throughout the Roman Empire on three missionary journeys, wrote 13 New Testament letters (possibly 14, if Hebrews is included), and shaped Christian theology more than any other individual. His letters address everything from justification by faith to the resurrection, from church order to marriage, from slavery to spiritual gifts.

Paul''s life wasn''t easy after conversion: he lists beatings, stonings, shipwrecks, imprisonments, and constant danger (2 Corinthians 11). Yet he called these "light and momentary troubles" compared to eternal glory. His life demonstrates that God can transform the most unlikely person into a powerful instrument, and that suffering for Christ is actually a privilege (Philippians 1:29).'
WHERE slug = 'life-of-paul-21';

-- Life of Peter 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Peter (originally Simon) was a fisherman from Bethsaida who became the most prominent of Jesus'' twelve apostles. His name appears first in every list of the Twelve. Jesus gave him the Aramaic name "Cephas" (Greek: "Peter"), meaning "rock"—ironic for a man known for impulsive speech and spectacular failures.

Peter''s story is full of extremes: he walked on water and then sank, confessed Jesus as Messiah and then rebuked Jesus for predicting His death, drew his sword to defend Jesus and then denied knowing Him three times. After the resurrection, Jesus restored Peter with three questions paralleling his three denials (John 21).

The Peter who preached at Pentecost and led the early church was transformed from the impulsive fisherman. Yet he still struggled—Paul confronted him for hypocrisy at Antioch (Galatians 2). Peter''s letters, written late in life, show a mature leader who had learned humility through failure. His story encourages us that Jesus doesn''t give up on us even when we fail repeatedly.'
WHERE slug = 'life-of-peter-14';

-- Women of Bible 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Bible was written in patriarchal cultures, yet it elevates women in remarkable ways. From Eve to Mary the mother of Jesus, women play crucial roles in salvation history. This study examines key women who shaped the biblical narrative through faith, courage, and obedience.

In the Old Testament, we find Sarah believing God''s impossible promise, Rahab hiding the spies, Ruth''s loyal love, Deborah leading Israel, Esther risking death to save her people, and Hannah''s prayer for a son. Each story reveals aspects of God''s character and plan.

The New Testament continues this pattern. Mary''s "yes" to God brought the Messiah into the world. Women followed Jesus, supported His ministry financially, stayed at the cross when disciples fled, and were first witnesses of the resurrection—a remarkable fact since women''s testimony wasn''t legally valid in that culture. Paul greeted numerous women leaders in his letters. The Bible''s treatment of women was countercultural in its time and remains relevant today.'
WHERE slug = 'women-of-bible-14';

-- Elijah and Elisha 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Elijah and Elisha were prophets during Israel''s darkest spiritual period—the reign of Ahab and Jezebel (around 870-850 BC). Ahab did "more evil in the eyes of the LORD than any of those before him" (1 Kings 16:30), introducing Baal worship on a massive scale through his Phoenician wife Jezebel.

Elijah burst onto the scene with no backstory, announcing a drought as judgment for idolatry. His confrontation with 450 prophets of Baal on Mount Carmel is one of Scripture''s most dramatic moments. Yet after this victory, Elijah fled from Jezebel''s threat and asked God to let him die—showing that even great faith can falter.

Elisha received a "double portion" of Elijah''s spirit and performed twice as many miracles. Where Elijah was often solitary and confrontational, Elisha worked more among ordinary people with acts of compassion. Together, their ministries demonstrate God''s power over nature, nations, and death—foreshadowing the greater Prophet to come (Jesus), whom Elijah and Moses met on the Mount of Transfiguration.'
WHERE slug = 'elijah-elisha-14';

-- ============================================
-- TOPICAL STUDIES
-- ============================================

-- Armor of God 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Paul''s famous armor passage (Ephesians 6:10-20) was written from prison, likely chained to Roman soldiers day and night. His vivid description of spiritual armor draws from the soldiers he observed, transforming military equipment into spiritual metaphors.

The passage begins with the reality of spiritual warfare: our struggle isn''t against flesh and blood but against cosmic powers of darkness. Paul wasn''t suggesting Christians are soldiers at war with other humans; our enemy is Satan and his forces. The armor is defensive—we stand and withstand, rather than attack.

Each piece serves a purpose: the belt of truth holds everything together, the breastplate of righteousness protects our vital organs, the gospel of peace gives us sure footing, the shield of faith extinguishes flaming arrows, the helmet of salvation protects our minds, and the sword of the Spirit (God''s Word) is our only offensive weapon. Notice that there''s no armor for the back—we''re not designed to retreat. The armor isn''t about our strength but about God''s provision.'
WHERE slug = 'armor-of-god-7';

-- Beatitudes 9 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Beatitudes (Matthew 5:3-12) open Jesus'' Sermon on the Mount—His most comprehensive teaching on kingdom living. The word "beatitude" comes from Latin "beatus" (blessed). Jesus pronounces blessing on eight unexpected groups, turning worldly values upside down.

Jesus likely spoke from a hillside near Capernaum overlooking the Sea of Galilee. His audience included disciples and crowds who expected the Messiah to overthrow Rome and establish political power. Instead, Jesus described the character of kingdom citizens: poor in spirit, mourning, meek, hungry for righteousness, merciful, pure in heart, peacemakers, and persecuted.

Each beatitude contains a present reality ("blessed are...") and a future promise ("for they will..."). The word "blessed" (Greek: makarios) means more than happy—it describes the deep flourishing of those rightly related to God regardless of circumstances. The Beatitudes aren''t eight different types of people but a unified portrait of every citizen of God''s kingdom. They describe Jesus Himself, who perfectly embodied each quality.'
WHERE slug = 'beatitudes-9-days';

-- Faith and Trust 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Faith is the cornerstone of Christian life—"without faith it is impossible to please God" (Hebrews 11:6). Yet faith is widely misunderstood. It''s not positive thinking, wishful hoping, or blind belief. Biblical faith is confident trust in God based on His revealed character and promises.

The Bible uses several Hebrew and Greek words for faith, trust, and belief. The Old Testament word "emunah" emphasizes steadfastness and reliability—faith that holds firm. The New Testament "pistis" includes belief, trust, and faithfulness. Faith is both a gift from God (Ephesians 2:8) and something we exercise and grow (Luke 17:5).

Hebrews 11 defines faith as "confidence in what we hope for and assurance about what we do not see" (11:1). It''s not belief without evidence but trust beyond what we can see, based on God''s track record. Abraham believed God''s promise and "it was credited to him as righteousness" (Genesis 15:6)—the same way we are justified today. This study explores how to grow in faith that transforms daily living.'
WHERE slug = 'faith-and-trust-21';

-- Forgiveness 10 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Forgiveness lies at the heart of the gospel. The God who "forgives all your sins" (Psalm 103:3) commands us to forgive others as we''ve been forgiven (Ephesians 4:32). Yet few commands are harder to obey, especially when the wound is deep.

Biblical forgiveness isn''t pretending nothing happened, minimizing harm, or automatically restoring trust. It''s a decision to release the debt owed us, refusing to hold the offense against the offender, and entrusting justice to God. Forgiveness may be instant; rebuilding trust takes time and requires the offender''s repentance.

Jesus told Peter to forgive "seventy-seven times" (Matthew 18:22)—not a literal count but limitless forgiveness. He illustrated this with a parable: a servant forgiven millions was unwilling to forgive a fellow servant pennies. The point is devastating: compared to our sin against God, any offense against us is infinitely smaller. Those who''ve experienced God''s forgiveness cannot withhold it from others. Unforgiveness binds us; forgiveness sets us free.'
WHERE slug = 'forgiveness-10-days';

-- Forgiveness in Relationships
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Unforgiveness is like drinking poison and expecting the other person to die. It binds us to the past, fuels bitterness, and blocks God''s work in our lives. Yet forgiveness can seem impossible when wounds are deep—abuse, betrayal, abandonment.

Jesus modeled forgiveness from the cross: "Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing" (Luke 23:34). Stephen echoed this as he was stoned to death. But Jesus and Stephen weren''t pretending their pain didn''t exist or that their persecutors were right. Forgiveness acknowledges the wrong while choosing not to hold it against the offender.

This study explores forgiveness in practical relationships: marriage, family, friendships, workplace. We''ll examine what forgiveness is and isn''t, how to forgive when we don''t feel like it, the difference between forgiveness and reconciliation, and how to set healthy boundaries while still forgiving. The goal isn''t cheap grace but the freedom and healing that comes when we stop carrying others'' offenses.'
WHERE slug = 'forgiveness-relationships';

-- Fruit of the Spirit 9 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The "fruit of the Spirit" (Galatians 5:22-23) describes the character that the Holy Spirit produces in believers: love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control. It''s singular "fruit," not "fruits"—these are an integrated whole, not a menu to choose from.

Paul contrasts Spirit-fruit with "works of the flesh" (5:19-21). Flesh produces acts; the Spirit produces character. Fleshly sins are obvious and destructive; Spirit-fruit is beautiful and life-giving. The contrast reveals a fundamental truth: we can''t manufacture Christian character through willpower. It grows as we "keep in step with the Spirit" (5:25).

The nine-fold fruit divides naturally into three triads. Love, joy, and peace describe our relationship with God. Patience, kindness, and goodness shape our relationships with others. Faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control govern our relationship with ourselves. Together they paint a portrait of Christ-like character—for Jesus perfectly embodied all nine. This study examines each quality, showing how to cultivate conditions for the Spirit''s fruit to grow.'
WHERE slug = 'fruit-of-spirit-9';

-- Holy Spirit 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Holy Spirit is the most misunderstood Person of the Trinity. Some traditions barely mention Him; others focus so exclusively on dramatic gifts that His primary work is obscured. The Bible presents the Spirit as fully God, personally active from creation to consummation.

In the Old Testament, the Spirit was present at creation (Genesis 1:2), empowered judges and kings for specific tasks, and spoke through prophets. But His presence was selective and temporary—He "came upon" individuals for specific purposes. The prophets looked forward to a day when God would pour out His Spirit on all people (Joel 2:28-29).

Jesus promised His disciples something better than His physical presence: the Spirit dwelling within (John 14-16). At Pentecost, this promise was fulfilled spectacularly. Now every believer is indwelt, sealed, and gifted by the Spirit. His primary work is pointing to Jesus (John 16:14), producing Christ-like character (Galatians 5:22-23), and empowering witness (Acts 1:8). This study explores who the Spirit is and how to live in conscious dependence on His power.'
WHERE slug = 'holy-spirit-14';

-- Prayer 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Prayer is the Christian''s lifeline to God—conversation with the Creator of the universe who invites us to call Him "Abba, Father." Yet many believers struggle with prayer, finding it boring, ineffective, or overwhelming. This study explores how Jesus taught and practiced prayer.

Jesus'' model prayer (Matthew 6:9-13) begins with worship ("hallowed be your name"), then kingdom priorities ("your kingdom come"), then personal requests ("give us... forgive us... lead us"). This order is intentional: we align our hearts with God''s purposes before bringing our needs.

Prayer in Scripture is remarkably diverse: praise and lament, confession and thanksgiving, intercession and petition, individual and corporate. The Psalms alone contain every type. The New Testament adds praying "in Jesus'' name" (accessing the Father through Christ''s mediation) and "in the Spirit" (with supernatural help when we don''t know how to pray). Prayer isn''t about technique but relationship—talking with a Father who loves to give good gifts to His children.'
WHERE slug = 'prayer-14-days';

-- Sermon on the Mount 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Sermon on the Mount (Matthew 5-7) is Jesus'' most famous teaching and the longest continuous discourse in the Gospels. Delivered early in His ministry to disciples and crowds on a hillside in Galilee, it describes life in God''s kingdom—a righteousness that surpasses the Pharisees'' external compliance.

The sermon is revolutionary. It goes beyond the Law''s prohibitions to address heart attitudes: not just murder but anger, not just adultery but lust, not just oaths but complete integrity. It commands impossible things: love your enemies, turn the other cheek, be perfect as your heavenly Father is perfect.

This isn''t a new legalism—a longer list of rules to fail. Jesus assumes His hearers know they cannot achieve this righteousness on their own. The sermon drives us to grace, showing our need for the very Savior who speaks these words. Once we receive His righteousness by faith, the Spirit begins transforming us into people who increasingly embody these kingdom values. The sermon describes both our goal and our gradual growth.'
WHERE slug = 'sermon-on-mount-7';

-- Spiritual Growth 30 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Every living thing grows—or it''s dying. Spiritual growth isn''t optional for Christians; it''s commanded. Peter concludes his final letter with "grow in the grace and knowledge of our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ" (2 Peter 3:18). But how does spiritual growth actually happen?

The Bible uses organic metaphors: we''re planted trees (Psalm 1), vines and branches (John 15), seeds in soil (Matthew 13). Growth happens gradually, often imperceptibly, requiring proper conditions: good soil, water, sunlight. We can''t make ourselves grow through sheer willpower, but we can cultivate conditions conducive to growth.

The "means of grace" are God''s ordinary channels for growth: Scripture, prayer, worship, fellowship, sacraments, and service. As we engage these disciplines, the Spirit works transformation. Growth also comes through trials—James says to "consider it pure joy" when facing trials because they produce perseverance and maturity (James 1:2-4). This study provides a month-long guide to understanding and pursuing spiritual growth.'
WHERE slug = 'spiritual-growth-30';

-- Ten Commandments 10 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Ten Commandments (Exodus 20:1-17) are the foundation of biblical ethics. Given at Mount Sinai about three months after the Exodus, they represent God''s covenant expectations for His redeemed people. Importantly, they follow the declaration: "I am the LORD your God, who brought you out of Egypt." Grace precedes law.

The commandments divide into two tables: the first four govern our relationship with God (no other gods, no idols, no misusing God''s name, keep the Sabbath); the last six govern relationships with others (honor parents, don''t murder, don''t commit adultery, don''t steal, don''t bear false witness, don''t covet). Jesus summarized them as loving God wholeheartedly and loving neighbor as ourselves (Matthew 22:37-40).

The commandments aren''t arbitrary rules but reflections of God''s character. Theft is wrong because God is faithful. Murder is wrong because God is life. Adultery is wrong because God is loyal. Understanding the "why" behind each command deepens our appreciation of God and our desire to obey—not to earn salvation but because we''ve already received it.'
WHERE slug = 'ten-commandments-10';

-- Wisdom for Life 30 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Biblical wisdom isn''t just knowledge—it''s skill in living. The Hebrew word "chokmah" describes the craftsmanship needed to build the tabernacle and the discernment needed to navigate life. Wisdom is applied knowledge, knowing what to do with what you know.

The wisdom books (Job, Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Songs, and many Psalms) address practical questions: How should I handle money? Choose a spouse? Raise children? Respond to injustice? Deal with suffering? Make decisions? Their counsel is grounded in "the fear of the LORD"—the foundational respect for God that is "the beginning of wisdom" (Proverbs 9:10).

Proverbs presents wisdom as a woman calling in the streets, inviting the simple to turn in. Wisdom can be sought, found, and learned—it''s not reserved for the naturally intelligent. James promises that God gives wisdom "generously to all without finding fault" (James 1:5). This study surveys biblical wisdom literature, applying its insights to contemporary situations.'
WHERE slug = 'wisdom-for-life-30';

-- ============================================
-- LIFE SITUATIONS
-- ============================================

-- Anxiety and Peace 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Anxiety is the most common mental health issue worldwide, affecting 284 million people. The Bible takes anxiety seriously—"do not be anxious" appears repeatedly, and Jesus devoted significant teaching to worry (Matthew 6:25-34). Yet these commands aren''t dismissive; they''re paired with promises and practices.

The Greek word for anxiety (merimnao) literally means "to divide the mind"—pulled in different directions, unable to focus on the present because we''re projecting feared futures. Jesus acknowledged life''s genuine concerns but pointed to a Father who knows our needs and cares more than He does for birds and flowers.

Paul''s famous command to "not be anxious about anything" (Philippians 4:6-7) was written from prison to people facing persecution. This wasn''t naive optimism. Paul offered a practice: turn anxiety into prayer, presenting requests with thanksgiving. The result? "The peace of God, which transcends all understanding, will guard your hearts and minds." This study explores Scripture''s rich teaching on trading anxiety for peace.'
WHERE slug = 'peace-over-anxiety-14';

-- Financial Wisdom 10 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus spoke more about money than about heaven and hell combined. About 15% of His recorded teaching concerns finances—not because God needs our money, but because how we handle money reveals what we truly trust. "For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also" (Matthew 6:21).

The Bible contains over 2,300 verses about money and possessions. They teach contentment (1 Timothy 6:6-10), generosity (2 Corinthians 9:6-7), planning (Proverbs 21:5), avoiding debt (Proverbs 22:7), and honest business practices (Proverbs 11:1). The overarching principle is stewardship: we own nothing; we manage what belongs to God.

This study applies biblical principles to practical finances: budgeting, giving, saving, spending, and investing. The goal isn''t prosperity but faithfulness. Jesus warned repeatedly about wealth''s spiritual dangers—it can choke the seed of God''s Word (Matthew 13:22) and make entering the kingdom harder than a camel through a needle''s eye (Matthew 19:24). Proper handling of money frees us to serve God rather than mammon.'
WHERE slug = 'financial-wisdom-10';

-- Grief and Comfort 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Grief is the price of love. When we lose someone or something precious, pain is the natural response. The Bible doesn''t suppress grief—Jesus Himself wept at Lazarus''s tomb even though He was about to raise him (John 11:35). The Psalms overflow with lament. Ecclesiastes affirms "a time to weep and a time to laugh, a time to mourn and a time to dance" (3:4).

Yet Christians grieve differently—not without hope. Paul wrote to the Thessalonians about deceased believers: "We do not want you to... grieve like the rest of mankind, who have no hope" (1 Thessalonians 4:13). Hope doesn''t eliminate grief but transforms it. We grieve real loss while trusting in resurrection, reunion, and God''s promise to wipe away every tear.

This study walks through the grief journey with Scripture as a guide. We''ll encounter psalms of lament, Jesus'' comfort to mourners, Paul''s hope of resurrection, and Revelation''s vision of a world without death. The Bible doesn''t offer platitudes but presence—the God who suffered with us and will one day end all suffering.'
WHERE slug = 'grief-and-comfort-14';

-- Hope in Hard Times 10 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Biblical hope isn''t wishful thinking—"I hope it doesn''t rain." It''s confident expectation based on God''s character and promises. The Hebrew word (tikvah) pictures a cord or rope, something to hold onto. Hope anchors the soul (Hebrews 6:19) when life''s storms threaten to sweep us away.

Hard times take many forms: illness, job loss, broken relationships, depression, persecution, natural disasters. The Bible doesn''t promise exemption from suffering but equips us for it. Romans 5:3-5 describes a surprising chain reaction: suffering produces perseverance, perseverance produces character, character produces hope—and this hope "does not put us to shame."

The ultimate ground of Christian hope is resurrection. Because Christ rose, death doesn''t have the final word. Our present sufferings, Paul writes, "are not worth comparing with the glory that will be revealed in us" (Romans 8:18). This study explores how hope sustains us in difficulty—not by denying pain but by placing it in perspective of God''s larger story.'
WHERE slug = 'hope-in-hard-times-10';

-- Marriage 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Marriage was God''s idea—the first human institution, established before the fall, designed for human flourishing. Genesis 2 records that God saw Adam''s loneliness and declared it "not good"—the first thing in creation so described. He created Eve and brought her to Adam, establishing the pattern of a man leaving father and mother and being united to his wife (2:24).

Marriage in Scripture is a covenant, not merely a contract. Contracts can be broken if terms aren''t met; covenants involve vows, witnesses, and commitment regardless of circumstances. God uses marriage as the primary metaphor for His relationship with His people—Israel as His bride in the Old Testament, the church as Christ''s bride in the New.

This study explores God''s design for marriage: complementary roles, sacrificial love, sexual intimacy, communication, conflict resolution, and building a God-centered home. Whether you''re preparing for marriage, strengthening your marriage, or serving as a friend of marriage, these truths provide the foundation for covenant relationship as God intended.'
WHERE slug = 'marriage-14-days';

-- Parenting 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Parenting is one of life''s most demanding and rewarding callings. The Bible doesn''t offer a step-by-step manual but provides principles that have guided parents for millennia. The foundational command is Deuteronomy 6:6-7: "These commandments that I give you today are to be on your hearts. Impress them on your children."

Biblical parenting involves both nurture and discipline. Ephesians 6:4 commands fathers: "Do not exasperate your children; instead, bring them up in the training and instruction of the Lord." Training (paideia) includes correction and discipline; instruction (nouthesia) involves verbal teaching. Both require relationship—children must know they''re loved to receive correction well.

Proverbs contains extensive parenting wisdom: the importance of discipline (13:24; 22:6), the danger of overindulgence (29:15), the power of a godly example (20:7), and the goal of raising children who choose wisdom (2:1-5). This study applies Scripture''s parenting principles to contemporary challenges, from discipline approaches to screen time, from building character to releasing adult children.'
WHERE slug = 'parenting-14-days';

-- Parenting with Godly Wisdom
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Modern parenting advice often contradicts itself: be strict vs. be permissive, praise everything vs. let them fail. The Bible offers a more coherent vision rooted in the character of God, who is both perfectly loving and perfectly holy, merciful and just, gracious and disciplining.

The goal of Christian parenting isn''t well-behaved children (though that''s nice) but disciples who love and follow Jesus. "A child left to himself disgraces his mother" (Proverbs 29:15), but trained children eventually "call [their mother] blessed" (Proverbs 31:28). This training is holistic: heart, mind, and behavior.

This study addresses real parenting challenges: how to discipline without exasperating, teach faith without forcing it, set boundaries while encouraging independence, navigate the teen years, and maintain influence as children become adults. The Proverbs''s wisdom, Jesus''s treatment of children, and Paul''s instructions to families provide timeless guidance for raising the next generation to know and serve God.'
WHERE slug = 'parenting-godly-wisdom';

-- Work and Calling 10 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Work isn''t a result of the fall—it was given before sin entered. God put Adam in the Garden "to work it and take care of it" (Genesis 2:15). The fall cursed work with thorns and sweat, but work itself is good. God Himself is a worker, and we bear His image when we create, serve, and produce.

The Bible rejects both the worship of work (making career our identity and security) and the despising of work (seeing it merely as necessary evil). Work is ministry. Paul told slaves—the lowest workers in Roman society—that they were actually "serving the Lord, not people" (Colossians 3:23-24).

Luther and the Reformers recovered the concept of vocation (calling). Every legitimate occupation can be a calling from God—not just "full-time ministry." The accountant who keeps honest books, the nurse who cares for the sick, the parent who raises children, the janitor who creates clean spaces—all can glorify God through their work. This study explores how to integrate faith and work, finding purpose and witness in daily labor.'
WHERE slug = 'work-and-calling-10';

-- ============================================
-- SEASONAL AND SPECIAL
-- ============================================

-- Advent 25 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Advent (from Latin "adventus," meaning "coming") is the Christian season of anticipation before Christmas. For centuries, believers have used these weeks to prepare their hearts for celebrating Jesus'' birth and to remember His promised return.

The season captures the longing of Old Testament believers who waited centuries for the Messiah. Israel had endured exile, foreign occupation, and 400 years of prophetic silence before the angel appeared to Zechariah. Simeon and Anna had waited their entire lives to see God''s salvation. Advent invites us to enter their waiting.

This reading plan journeys through prophecies, promises, and preparations leading to Bethlehem. We''ll read Isaiah''s Servant Songs, Micah''s prediction of Bethlehem, the genealogies showing Jesus'' lineage, the angelic announcements, Mary''s song, and finally the birth narratives. The goal isn''t just information but transformation—letting the wonder of incarnation refresh hearts grown overfamiliar with the Christmas story.'
WHERE slug = 'advent-25-days';

-- Christmas Story 7 Days (duplicate reference)
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Christmas story is so familiar it can lose its power. Nativity scenes, carols, and cultural traditions sometimes obscure the radical nature of the incarnation: the eternal God entering creation as a helpless infant, born to an unwed teenage girl in an occupied nation, laid in an animal''s feeding trough.

The birth narratives in Matthew and Luke complement each other. Matthew writes from Joseph''s perspective, emphasizing fulfilled prophecy and Jesus as Israel''s King. Luke writes from Mary''s viewpoint, focusing on the marginalized: a humble virgin, elderly Elizabeth, shepherds (considered unclean by religious elites). Together they reveal a God who identifies with the lowly.

This seven-day plan reads through both accounts in their entirety, along with the profound theological reflection in John 1 and Philippians 2. We''ll encounter the prophecies, the announcements, the songs of Mary and Zechariah, the birth, the shepherds and magi, and the significance of "the Word became flesh." Let the familiar become fresh.'
WHERE slug = 'christmas-story-7';

-- Easter Journey 7 Days (duplicate reference)
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Easter isn''t just a holiday—it''s the hinge of history. If Christ didn''t rise, Paul wrote, "your faith is futile; you are still in your sins" (1 Corinthians 15:17). But if He did rise, everything changes: death is defeated, sin is conquered, and eternal life is secured for all who believe.

This plan walks through the final week of Jesus'' life—the week that occupies roughly one-third of each Gospel. From the Triumphal Entry through betrayal, trial, crucifixion, and resurrection, these events unfold with deliberate purpose. Jesus wasn''t a victim of circumstances but the Lamb slain "from the creation of the world" (Revelation 13:8).

Each day focuses on different aspects of Passion Week: the temple cleansing, the Last Supper, Gethsemane, the trials, crucifixion, burial, and resurrection. The goal is slow, reflective reading—letting the familiar narrative pierce fresh. "Were you there when they crucified my Lord?" asks the old spiritual. This plan helps you be there, in heart and imagination.'
WHERE slug = 'easter-journey-7';

-- Lent 40 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Lent is the 40-day season (excluding Sundays) before Easter, traditionally a time of preparation through fasting, prayer, and repentance. The number 40 echoes significant biblical periods: Israel''s 40 years in the wilderness, Moses''s 40 days on Sinai, Elijah''s 40-day journey, and Jesus'' 40 days of temptation.

Early Christians observed Lent as final preparation for those about to be baptized at Easter, but it soon expanded to the whole church. The season invites self-examination, confession, and renewed commitment. It''s not about earning God''s favor through self-denial but creating space to experience His grace more deeply.

This reading plan follows Jesus from His baptism through resurrection, paralleling His journey with our own. We''ll examine our hearts, confront our sin, embrace the cross, and emerge at Easter with renewed joy in the risen Christ. The disciplines of Lent aren''t punitive but preparatory—loosening our grip on lesser things to hold more tightly to Christ.'
WHERE slug = 'lent-40-days';

-- New Year Fresh Start 7 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'New Year''s resolutions have an abysmal success rate—about 80% fail by February. Perhaps that''s because willpower alone can''t produce lasting change. Scripture offers a different approach: transformation through renewed minds, empowered by the Spirit, grounded in grace rather than guilt.

The Bible is full of new beginnings: creation, the flood, the exodus, the return from exile, the resurrection. Each demonstrates God''s ability to make all things new. Paul writes, "If anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come: The old has gone, the new is here!" (2 Corinthians 5:17). This newness isn''t self-generated; it''s received.

This seven-day plan helps you start the year with eternal perspective. We''ll examine priorities, goals, relationships, and habits through Scripture''s lens. The focus isn''t on making resolutions you''ll break but on positioning yourself to receive what God wants to do. As you commit your way to the Lord and trust in Him, He will act (Psalm 37:5).'
WHERE slug = 'new-year-fresh-start-7';

-- ============================================
-- FOUNDATIONAL / INTRODUCTORY
-- ============================================

-- 7 Day Faith Reset
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Sometimes we need to return to basics. Life gets complicated, faith feels stale, and we lose sight of what matters most. A "reset" doesn''t mean starting over but returning to firm foundations—the core truths that anchor everything else.

This seven-day plan revisits Christianity''s essentials: who God is, who Jesus is, what He accomplished, how we receive salvation, and how we live as His followers. Whether you''re new to faith or have walked with God for decades, these fundamentals never become obsolete. They''re the soil from which everything else grows.

Each day focuses on one foundational truth, with Scripture to read and questions to ponder. The goal isn''t just information but encounter—meeting God fresh in His Word. Like a computer reboot that clears glitches and restores optimal function, a faith reset clears accumulated confusion and restores clarity about what matters most: knowing Christ and making Him known.'
WHERE slug = '7-day-faith-reset';

-- 21 Day Renewal
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Research suggests it takes about 21 days to form a new habit. This plan uses that timeframe to establish rhythms of Scripture reading and application that can become lifelong practices. It''s not a quick fix but a launching pad for sustained growth.

Spiritual renewal isn''t primarily about trying harder but about receiving more. Romans 12:2 commands "be transformed by the renewing of your mind"—the passive voice indicates God''s work in us. Yet we cooperate by presenting ourselves to Him and saturating our minds with truth. This plan combines both: encountering God''s Word and actively responding.

Over 21 days, we''ll cover key themes: God''s character, our identity in Christ, the Spirit''s work, spiritual disciplines, relationships, and mission. Each day includes Scripture reading, reflection questions, and a practical application. The goal is building patterns that continue long after the plan ends—habits of grace that position us for ongoing transformation.'
WHERE slug = '21-day-renewal';

-- 30 Day Walk with Jesus
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'A month with Jesus—walking where He walked, hearing what He taught, watching how He lived. This plan reads through the Gospels thematically, organizing Jesus'' life and teaching into 30 digestible portions that reveal His character, mission, and relevance for today.

Jesus is Christianity''s center. Paul''s ambition was "to know Christ" (Philippians 3:10). John wrote his Gospel so readers "may believe that Jesus is the Messiah" and "have life in his name" (John 20:31). The writer of Hebrews urges us to fix our eyes on Jesus (12:2). All theology, ethics, and practice must be rooted in who Jesus is and what He did.

Each day focuses on an aspect of Jesus'' person or work: His divine nature, human nature, teaching, miracles, relationships, prayers, death, and resurrection. We''ll see Him with fresh eyes—not the domesticated Jesus of cultural Christianity but the radical, compassionate, authoritative Lord who changed history and changes lives.'
WHERE slug = '30-day-walk-jesus';

-- 90 Day New Believer
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'New life in Christ is the greatest gift—but it can also feel overwhelming. There''s so much to learn, and longtime Christians sometimes assume knowledge that new believers don''t have. This 90-day plan provides a thorough foundation for those new to faith.

The plan covers essential topics in four phases. Month 1 establishes basics: who God is, what Jesus did, how salvation works, and how to read the Bible and pray. Month 2 deepens understanding: the Holy Spirit, the church, spiritual growth, and handling doubt. Month 3 applies faith to life: relationships, work, suffering, and sharing your faith.

Think of this as discipleship in a box—the conversations you''d have with a mentor condensed into daily readings. Each day includes Scripture, explanation, and next steps. The goal isn''t just knowledge but transformation: moving from newborn to growing Christian, equipped to walk with God and serve others. Welcome to the family of faith.'
WHERE slug = '90-day-new-believer';

-- Basics of Faith 14 Days (duplicate reference)
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Christianity rests on foundational truths that have been believed "always, everywhere, by everyone" (to quote Vincent of Lérins). These basics distinguish authentic faith from counterfeits and unite believers across traditions and centuries.

This plan covers the essentials: God''s existence and character, Scripture''s authority, humanity''s condition, Christ''s person and work, salvation by grace through faith, the Holy Spirit''s role, the church''s nature, and future hope. These aren''t peripheral matters but the non-negotiables of Christian faith.

The Apostles'' Creed, formulated in the early church, summarizes these basics in a few sentences. Early Christians memorized it as part of baptismal preparation. This plan expands on each phrase, grounding ancient confession in Scripture. Whether you''re new to faith or want a refresher, these two weeks will strengthen your grip on truth that has anchored believers for 2,000 years.'
WHERE slug = 'basics-of-faith-14';

-- What is Salvation
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The word "salvation" means rescue or deliverance—but from what? To what? How? These questions get to Christianity''s heart. The gospel ("good news") only makes sense against the backdrop of bad news: humanity''s sin and its consequences.

The Bible uses rich vocabulary to describe salvation: justification (declared righteous), redemption (bought back from slavery), reconciliation (restored relationship), adoption (welcomed into family), regeneration (made spiritually alive), and sanctification (made holy). Each metaphor illuminates a different aspect of what Christ accomplished.

This study traces salvation''s storyline from Genesis to Revelation. We''ll see how sin severed relationship with God, why human efforts can''t fix the problem, what Christ''s death and resurrection accomplished, how faith receives what grace offers, and what salvation means for daily living and eternal destiny. Understanding salvation deeply enables us to rest in Christ more fully and explain the gospel more clearly.'
WHERE slug = 'what-is-salvation';

-- Bible in a Year
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Reading the entire Bible in one year is an ambitious but achievable goal. It requires about 15-20 minutes of reading per day—roughly three to four chapters. Millions of Christians have done it, gaining an overview of Scripture''s grand narrative and a discipline of daily engagement with God''s Word.

This plan follows a chronological approach, reading biblical events in the order they happened rather than the order books appear in the Bible. This helps you see how history unfolded and how different books relate to their historical context. You''ll read parts of Psalms and Proverbs throughout the year for variety.

The key to success is consistency, not perfection. If you miss a day, don''t try to catch up immediately—just pick up where the plan indicates. It''s better to read steadily than to burn out trying to read multiple days at once. By year''s end, you''ll have encountered the whole counsel of God, understanding the Bible''s overarching story from creation to new creation.'
WHERE slug = 'bible-in-a-year';

-- One Year Bible Overview
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'A year-long journey through Scripture''s major themes and stories provides comprehensive biblical literacy without requiring you to read every verse. This overview plan hits the highlights—the essential narratives, teachings, and passages that form the Bible''s backbone.

The plan is designed for busy people who want substantive engagement with Scripture without overwhelming reading loads. Each day focuses on a manageable portion with context explaining significance. You''ll read creation, fall, flood, and Babel; the patriarchs and exodus; the conquest and kingdom; the prophets and exile; the Gospels and early church; the letters and Revelation.

By year''s end, you''ll have a mental map of the Bible''s story, knowing how the pieces fit together. This foundation makes future detailed study more fruitful—you''ll understand how any passage connects to the larger narrative of creation, fall, redemption, and restoration. Consider this your Bible overview course, taken at a sustainable daily pace.'
WHERE slug = 'one-year-bible-overview';

-- ============================================
-- ADDITIONAL TOPICAL STUDIES
-- ============================================

-- Authority of Scripture
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Christianity stands or falls on Scripture''s reliability. If the Bible is merely human opinion, we''re left guessing about God. If it''s God''s revealed Word, it carries ultimate authority for faith and life. This study examines what the Bible claims about itself and why those claims deserve our trust.

The doctrine of Scripture includes inspiration (God breathed it out through human authors), inerrancy (it''s truthful in all it affirms), sufficiency (it provides all we need for faith and godliness), and clarity (its main message can be understood). These aren''t arbitrary claims but what Scripture says about itself (2 Timothy 3:16; 2 Peter 1:20-21).

We''ll also examine how we got the Bible: how books were written, collected, and recognized as canonical. The process wasn''t arbitrary—early Christians recognized what was already authoritative, much like a person recognizes a friend''s voice on the phone. Understanding Scripture''s nature increases confidence in reading, studying, and applying it.'
WHERE slug = 'authority-of-scripture';

-- Character of God
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'A.W. Tozer wrote, "What comes into our minds when we think about God is the most important thing about us." Our view of God shapes everything: how we pray, how we handle suffering, how we relate to others, how we face death. Getting God right is the foundation of right living.

The Bible reveals God through His names, actions, and direct declarations of His attributes. He is holy (utterly set apart), loving (giving Himself for our good), just (always doing right), merciful (withholding deserved punishment), omniscient (knowing all things), omnipotent (all-powerful), omnipresent (everywhere), eternal (without beginning or end), and immutable (unchanging).

These attributes aren''t abstract theology but practical reality. God''s holiness means I must approach Him with reverence. His love means I can trust His intentions. His power means nothing is impossible for Him. His faithfulness means His promises are certain. This study examines God''s character attribute by attribute, showing how each transforms daily living.'
WHERE slug = 'character-of-god';

-- Covenants of the Bible
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Bible is structured around covenants—solemn agreements that define relationships between God and His people. Understanding these covenants unlocks Scripture''s storyline and shows how the Old and New Testaments connect.

The major biblical covenants include: the Noahic (promising never to flood the earth again), Abrahamic (promising land, descendants, and blessing to all nations), Mosaic (establishing Israel as God''s people through law), Davidic (promising an eternal kingdom through David''s line), and New (promising heart transformation and forgiveness through Christ).

Each covenant builds on previous ones, with the New Covenant fulfilling and surpassing them all. Jeremiah prophesied it (31:31-34); Jesus inaugurated it at the Last Supper ("this cup is the new covenant in my blood"). The writer of Hebrews explains how Christ''s priesthood and sacrifice makes the New Covenant superior to the Old. Understanding covenants helps us read the whole Bible as one unified story pointing to Christ.'
WHERE slug = 'covenants-of-bible';

-- Grace vs Works
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The relationship between grace and works has generated centuries of theological debate—and much confusion for ordinary believers. Are we saved by grace alone? What role do works play? Does it matter how we live if grace covers everything?

The Reformation recovered the biblical truth of "sola gratia" (grace alone) and "sola fide" (faith alone): we''re saved by grace alone through faith alone in Christ alone. Works can''t earn salvation—if they could, grace wouldn''t be grace (Romans 11:6). Yet genuine faith produces works—if it doesn''t, it''s dead (James 2:17).

This study harmonizes the New Testament''s teaching. Paul and James aren''t contradicting each other; they''re addressing different errors. Paul combated legalism (adding works to faith for salvation). James confronted empty profession (claiming faith without evidence). True salvation is by grace through faith, resulting in a transformed life of good works—not to earn salvation but because we''ve received it.'
WHERE slug = 'grace-vs-works';

-- Identity in Christ 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Who are you? The world answers with achievement, appearance, relationships, or possessions. Scripture offers a radically different identity—who you are in Christ. This identity doesn''t fluctuate with circumstances because it''s based on Christ''s unchanging work, not your performance.

Paul''s letters overflow with "in Christ" language. Believers are chosen, adopted, forgiven, sealed, and blessed "in Christ" (Ephesians 1). We''re new creations "in Christ" (2 Corinthians 5:17). We''re saints, not sinners trying to become saints. Understanding our position revolutionizes how we live.

This study examines key identity truths: you are forgiven (Ephesians 1:7), righteous (2 Corinthians 5:21), a child of God (John 1:12), a new creation (2 Corinthians 5:17), God''s workmanship (Ephesians 2:10), a temple of the Spirit (1 Corinthians 6:19), and more. Each truth is meant not just for mental assent but deep internalization. What you believe about who you are in Christ shapes everything else.'
WHERE slug = 'identity-in-christ-14';

-- Kingdom of God
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The kingdom of God was Jesus'' central message. He announced, "The kingdom of God has come near" (Mark 1:15), and His parables typically begin "The kingdom of God is like..." Yet the kingdom remains one of the most misunderstood concepts in Christianity.

The kingdom isn''t a place but God''s reign—His rule and authority exercised over willing subjects. It was present in Jesus'' ministry ("the kingdom of God is in your midst," Luke 17:21), advances through the church age, and will be consummated when Christ returns. We live in the "already but not yet"—the kingdom has been inaugurated but not yet fully realized.

Kingdom citizens live by kingdom values (the Sermon on the Mount), operate by kingdom power (the Holy Spirit), and anticipate kingdom consummation (Christ''s return). This study traces kingdom theme from Old Testament anticipation through Jesus'' proclamation to present application and future hope. Understanding the kingdom shapes how we pray ("your kingdom come"), live, and await Christ''s return.'
WHERE slug = 'kingdom-of-god';

-- Names of God 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'In ancient cultures, names revealed character. God''s names in Scripture aren''t arbitrary labels but revelations of who He is. Studying His names deepens our knowledge of His character and expands our vocabulary for addressing Him in prayer.

The foundational name is YHWH (Yahweh), revealed to Moses at the burning bush: "I AM WHO I AM" (Exodus 3:14). This mysterious name conveys self-existence, eternal presence, and covenant faithfulness. Devout Jews considered it too holy to pronounce, substituting "Adonai" (Lord) when reading aloud.

Other names reveal specific attributes: Elohim (mighty Creator), El Shaddai (God Almighty), El Elyon (God Most High), Jehovah-Jireh (the LORD provides), Jehovah-Rapha (the LORD who heals), Jehovah-Nissi (the LORD my banner), Jehovah-Shalom (the LORD is peace), and more. This study examines major divine names in their biblical contexts, showing what each reveals about God''s character and how that knowledge transforms worship and trust.'
WHERE slug = 'names-of-god-14';

-- Names of Jesus 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus is called by more than 200 names and titles in Scripture—each revealing an aspect of His person, work, or relationship to believers. These names weren''t chosen arbitrarily; they unveil the full glory of who Jesus is.

Some names emphasize deity: Word (John 1:1), I AM (John 8:58), Son of God, Alpha and Omega. Others emphasize humanity: Son of Man, Jesus (meaning "Yahweh saves"), Son of David. Others describe His work: Lamb of God, Savior, High Priest, Mediator. Still others picture His relationship with believers: Good Shepherd, Bread of Life, Light of the World, Friend.

This study examines Jesus'' major names in their biblical contexts. Each name becomes a window into Christ''s glory and a fresh way to worship Him. When we''re confused, we remember He''s the Truth. When we''re grieving, we remember He''s the Resurrection and Life. When we''re guilty, we remember He''s our Advocate. His names meet our every need.'
WHERE slug = 'names-of-jesus-14';

-- Spiritual Gifts Explained
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Every believer has at least one spiritual gift—a Spirit-empowered ability for building up the church. The New Testament lists various gifts in Romans 12, 1 Corinthians 12-14, Ephesians 4, and 1 Peter 4. Understanding spiritual gifts helps believers serve effectively and appreciate others'' contributions.

The gift lists differ somewhat, suggesting they''re illustrative rather than exhaustive. Some gifts are more "supernatural" (prophecy, healing, tongues), others more "natural" (teaching, giving, serving, administration). All are given by the Spirit (1 Corinthians 12:11), all are for the common good (12:7), and all are necessary (12:14-26).

This study examines major spiritual gifts, their biblical basis, and their contemporary application. We''ll address controversial questions: Are all gifts still operative today? How do we identify our gifts? What''s the relationship between gifts and fruit? The goal isn''t just knowledge but activation—discovering and deploying your gifts for God''s glory and the church''s good.'
WHERE slug = 'spiritual-gifts-explained';

-- Trinity Explained
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Trinity—one God existing eternally as three Persons: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit—is Christianity''s most distinctive and mysterious doctrine. It''s not found explicitly in any single verse but emerges from Scripture''s total testimony about God.

The doctrine developed as early Christians wrestled with biblical data: the Old Testament''s emphatic monotheism ("The LORD our God, the LORD is one," Deuteronomy 6:4) alongside New Testament revelation of Jesus'' deity and the Spirit''s personhood. The church councils of Nicaea (325) and Constantinople (381) articulated the doctrine against heresies that denied either God''s oneness or the full deity of each Person.

This study traces biblical evidence for the Trinity: Old Testament hints (plural pronouns, the Angel of the LORD, personified Wisdom), Jesus'' deity claims and divine actions, the Spirit''s personhood, and Trinitarian formulas (Matthew 28:19; 2 Corinthians 13:14). We can''t fully comprehend the Trinity—that would make God small enough for finite minds—but we can worship the God who reveals Himself as Father, Son, and Spirit.'
WHERE slug = 'trinity-explained';

-- ============================================
-- ADDITIONAL LIFE SITUATIONS
-- ============================================

-- Encouragement for Depression
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Depression affects millions of people, including many faithful believers. Elijah experienced it after his greatest victory, asking God to take his life (1 Kings 19). David described his soul as "downcast" (Psalm 42:5). Jeremiah has an entire book of Laments. The Bible doesn''t treat depression as automatic spiritual failure.

Yet Scripture also offers hope. God responded to Elijah not with rebuke but with rest, food, and fresh purpose. The Psalms model honest lament followed by chosen trust. Jesus promises rest for the weary (Matthew 11:28-30). The Spirit is called the Comforter. Depression may be a thorn we bear, but grace is sufficient (2 Corinthians 12:9).

This study isn''t a substitute for professional help when needed—depression often has physical components requiring medical attention. But Scripture provides spiritual resources: promises to cling to, prayers to pray, truth to combat lies, and hope that extends beyond this life. You''re not alone, and your story isn''t over.'
WHERE slug = 'encouragement-depression';

-- Rest for the Weary
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'We live in an exhausted culture. Busyness is worn as a badge of honor. Margins have disappeared. Devices keep us perpetually connected and perpetually drained. Yet Jesus invited: "Come to me, all you who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest" (Matthew 11:28).

Biblical rest isn''t laziness or escapism. God Himself rested on the seventh day—not from exhaustion but as a pattern for His creation. The Sabbath command (Exodus 20:8-11) institutionalized regular rest, trusting that God would provide even when work stopped. The promised land was described as God''s "rest" (Hebrews 4:1-11).

This study explores biblical rest: its basis in God''s character, its practice in rhythms of work and cessation, its ultimate fulfillment in Christ. We''ll examine practical applications: how to implement Sabbath principles, how to find soul rest amidst activity, how to trust God enough to stop. The world runs on anxiety; God''s people are invited to rest.'
WHERE slug = 'rest-for-weary';

-- Waiting on God''s Timing
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Waiting is one of life''s hardest disciplines. We want results now—answers, relief, change, fulfillment. But God often operates on a different timetable. Abraham waited 25 years for Isaac. Israel waited 400 years in Egypt. The prophets announced Messiah centuries before He came.

Biblical waiting isn''t passive resignation but active trust. "Wait for the LORD," the psalmist wrote; "be strong and take heart and wait for the LORD" (Psalm 27:14). Isaiah promises, "Those who wait on the LORD will renew their strength" (40:31). Waiting involves expectation—we''re not just killing time but anticipating God''s action.

This study explores waiting through Scripture''s examples: Abraham, Joseph, David, Hannah, Simeon, and others who trusted through prolonged uncertainty. We''ll examine what waiting produces (character, dependence, faith) and how to wait actively rather than anxiously. God''s delays aren''t denials; His timing is perfect even when it doesn''t match ours.'
WHERE slug = 'waiting-gods-timing';

-- Sharing Your Faith
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus'' final command was to "make disciples of all nations" (Matthew 28:19)—and that includes us. Yet many Christians feel inadequate for evangelism, unsure what to say or afraid of rejection. This study equips believers to share their faith naturally and effectively.

The New Testament shows varied approaches to evangelism. Peter preached to crowds at Pentecost. Philip explained Isaiah to an individual Ethiopian. Paul reasoned in synagogues and debated in Athens. Jesus'' conversations with Nicodemus and the Samaritan woman differed dramatically. There''s no single method, but there are consistent elements: knowing the gospel, caring for people, and depending on the Spirit.

This study covers gospel essentials (what must be communicated), personal testimony (your story of God''s work), common questions and objections, and practical opportunities in everyday life. The goal isn''t making you a professional evangelist but a faithful witness who naturally shares the hope within you (1 Peter 3:15) in your unique sphere of influence.'
WHERE slug = 'sharing-your-faith';

-- Living on Mission
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Mission isn''t just for missionaries. Every believer is sent into their world as Jesus was sent into the world (John 20:21). Your neighborhood, workplace, school, and social circles are your mission field. This study explores what it means to live intentionally as Christ''s ambassador wherever you are.

The early church didn''t build programs to reach outsiders—they lived such compelling lives that outsiders asked questions (1 Peter 3:15). They shared meals, cared for the sick, served the poor, and loved enemies. Their everyday lives were their primary witness, supplemented by verbal proclamation of the gospel.

This study examines missional living: seeing your life as a stewardship, viewing ordinary activities as ministry opportunities, building genuine relationships with non-believers, and integrating gospel proclamation with gospel demonstration. The goal is developing mission as a lifestyle, not adding another program to an already busy life. You are sent—live accordingly.'
WHERE slug = 'living-on-mission';

-- Power of Community
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Christianity was never meant to be solo. From "let us make man in our image" (the Trinity''s community) to the New Jerusalem where God dwells with His people, Scripture presents faith as inherently communal. The church isn''t an optional add-on but essential to Christian life.

The early church "devoted themselves to... fellowship" (Acts 2:42). They shared meals, property, joys, and sorrows. The New Testament contains over 50 "one another" commands: love one another, forgive one another, encourage one another, bear one another''s burdens. These can''t be fulfilled in isolation.

This study explores biblical community: its theological basis in God''s trinitarian nature, its practical expression in the local church, and its benefits for spiritual growth. We''ll address barriers to genuine community (busyness, individualism, past hurts) and practical steps toward deeper connection. God designed you for community—not just attendance at services but authentic relationships where iron sharpens iron.'
WHERE slug = 'power-of-community';

-- ============================================
-- MISCELLANEOUS REMAINING PLANS
-- ============================================

-- Bible 30 Minutes a Day
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Thirty minutes daily with Scripture can transform your life. This manageable commitment—less than 3% of your day—provides substantial engagement with God''s Word without overwhelming busy schedules. Consistency matters more than volume.

This plan teaches you how to read the Bible effectively: observation (what does it say?), interpretation (what does it mean?), and application (how should I respond?). We''ll cover various types of biblical literature and how to read each appropriately: narrative, poetry, prophecy, wisdom, gospel, and epistle.

The goal isn''t just reading but meeting God through His Word. The Bible isn''t merely information to master but a living word through which the living God speaks. As you establish this daily rhythm, you''ll find Scripture becoming not a duty but a delight—the means by which you hear your Father''s voice and align your life with His will.'
WHERE slug = 'bible-30-minutes-day';

-- Bible for Busy Christians
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'You''re busy. Between work, family, responsibilities, and crises, finding time for Bible reading can feel impossible. Yet Jesus said, "Man shall not live on bread alone, but on every word that comes from the mouth of God" (Matthew 4:4). Spiritual nourishment isn''t optional.

This plan is designed for real life. Readings are brief but substantive. Each day includes a key verse to memorize or meditate on throughout the day. The approach is quality over quantity—better to truly absorb a few verses than skim chapters without comprehension.

We''ll also discuss integrating Scripture into busy life: audio Bibles during commutes, verse apps for waiting moments, family devotions that don''t require hours, and sustainable rhythms. The goal isn''t guilt about what you''re not doing but grace-filled patterns you can actually maintain. Even small doses of God''s Word, consistently taken, produce great results over time.'
WHERE slug = 'bible-busy-christians';

-- Creation, Fall, Promise
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Bible''s first three chapters establish everything that follows. Creation reveals God''s character, power, and purpose for humanity. The Fall explains what went wrong with the world. The Promise (Genesis 3:15) announces God''s plan to fix it. This short plan examines these foundational chapters.

Genesis 1-2 presents God as the self-existent Creator who speaks the universe into being. Humanity is the pinnacle of creation, made in God''s image, given dominion and purpose. Everything is "very good." Understanding creation counters modern lies: that we''re accidents, that the material world is bad, that purpose must be invented rather than received.

Genesis 3 introduces the serpent''s temptation, humanity''s fall, and sin''s consequences. Yet even in pronouncing judgment, God promises that the woman''s offspring will crush the serpent''s head—the first gospel announcement (the "protoevangelium"). The rest of the Bible is the story of this promise''s unfolding and fulfillment in Christ.'
WHERE slug = 'creation-fall-promise';

-- Daily Proverbs and Psalms
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Proverbs has 31 chapters—one for each day of most months. Psalms has 150 chapters—five per day covers it in a month. This simple rhythm has been followed by believers for centuries, providing daily wisdom and worship without complicated reading plans.

The combination is powerful. Proverbs addresses horizontal relationships—how to live skillfully with others in the practical situations of daily life. Psalms address vertical relationship—how to worship, lament, confess, and praise before God. Together they shape both character and devotion.

This plan follows the classic pattern: read the Proverbs chapter matching today''s date, and read five Psalms. On the 31st of months with 30 days, read two chapters of Proverbs. The repetition is intentional—you''ll read these books 12 times yearly, and their wisdom will increasingly become part of you. This is formation through repetition, letting Scripture''s wisdom saturate your mind.'
WHERE slug = 'daily-proverbs-psalms';

-- Discipleship - Following Jesus
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus didn''t just call people to believe in Him—He called them to follow Him. "Come, follow me," He said to fishermen, tax collectors, and seekers. Discipleship means more than intellectual assent; it means arranging your entire life around Jesus as master, teacher, and Lord.

In Jesus'' day, disciples (students) attached themselves to rabbis (teachers), learning not just their teaching but their way of life. They traveled with their rabbi, observed him, imitated him, and eventually became like him. Jesus chose twelve to "be with him" before sending them out (Mark 3:14).

This study examines what it means to follow Jesus today: hearing His call, counting the cost, denying ourselves, taking up our cross daily, learning His teaching, imitating His example, being transformed into His likeness, and making other disciples. Discipleship isn''t a program but a lifestyle—the normal Christian life Jesus intended for all His followers.'
WHERE slug = 'discipleship-following-jesus';

-- Hope in Suffering
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Suffering raises life''s hardest questions. Why does God allow pain? Does suffering mean He doesn''t care or isn''t powerful? How do we maintain faith when life hurts? Scripture doesn''t give easy answers, but it provides profound resources for suffering well.

The Bible is honest about suffering. Job lost everything and questioned God. David cried out in anguish. Jeremiah wept over Jerusalem. Jesus Himself sweat drops of blood anticipating the cross. Scripture doesn''t pretend life is easy or that faith guarantees comfort.

Yet biblical sufferers found hope. Job encountered God directly and was satisfied without answers to his questions. The psalmists moved from lament to trust. Paul called his afflictions "light and momentary" compared to eternal glory (2 Corinthians 4:17). Jesus endured the cross "for the joy set before him" (Hebrews 12:2). This study walks through suffering with these guides, finding hope that sustains even when circumstances don''t change.'
WHERE slug = 'hope-in-suffering';

-- Joshua - Conquering Fear
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Joshua faced an impossible task: leading Israel into the Promised Land, conquering fortified cities, and defeating experienced armies—while following the irreplaceable Moses. No wonder God''s charge to him repeated "be strong and courageous" three times (Joshua 1:6-9).

The book of Joshua records Israel''s conquest and settlement of Canaan, showing God''s faithfulness to promises made to Abraham 600 years earlier. Its battles raise difficult questions for modern readers, but its spiritual lessons are timeless: courage based on God''s presence, obedience as the key to success, consequences of compromise, and the importance of choosing whom we will serve.

Joshua himself models godly leadership. He had served faithfully under Moses for 40 years before taking the lead. He listened to God, obeyed immediately, led from the front, and pointed people to the LORD rather than himself. His story shows that courage isn''t absence of fear but moving forward despite fear—because God is with us.'
WHERE slug = 'joshua-conquering-fear';

-- Judges - Rebellion and Grace
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Judges is one of the Bible''s darkest books. It records Israel''s downward spiral during the 300+ years between Joshua''s death and the monarchy. The repeated cycle—sin, oppression, crying out, deliverance, rest, then sin again—shows humanity''s persistent rebellion and God''s persistent grace.

The book''s refrain is haunting: "In those days Israel had no king; everyone did what was right in his own eyes" (Judges 21:25). The judges (military deliverers) grew increasingly flawed: from Othniel (exemplary) to Gideon (hesitant but faithful) to Jephthah (rash) to Samson (thoroughly compromised). The final chapters describe moral horrors.

Yet even in darkness, God''s grace persists. He raised up deliverers despite the people''s faithlessness. He preserved His people through their worst periods. And the book''s implicit cry—"We need a king!"—points forward to David and ultimately to Christ, the King who breaks the sin cycle once and for all.'
WHERE slug = 'judges-rebellion-grace';

-- Miracles of Jesus 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Gospels record about 37 miracles of Jesus—acts of supernatural power demonstrating His authority over nature, disease, demons, and death. These weren''t magic tricks or publicity stunts but "signs" revealing His identity and inaugurating God''s kingdom.

Jesus'' miracles were deliberate and purposeful. Each one taught something about who He was: calming the storm showed authority over nature (only God controls the sea in the Old Testament); healing diseases showed compassion and kingdom power; casting out demons demonstrated victory over Satan; raising the dead proved power over humanity''s ultimate enemy.

This study examines Jesus'' miracles in their contexts, asking what each reveals about Christ and His kingdom. We''ll also address questions about miracles today: Does God still heal? Why aren''t some people healed? How do we pray expectantly while accepting God''s sovereignty? The goal is encountering the powerful Jesus and trusting Him more fully.'
WHERE slug = 'miracles-of-jesus-21';

-- Parables of Jesus 21 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus was the master storyteller. About one-third of His recorded teaching comes in parables—earthly stories with heavenly meanings. These weren''t just illustrations but strategic teaching tools that revealed truth to seekers while hiding it from the merely curious (Matthew 13:10-17).

Parables draw from everyday life: seeds and soil, sheep and shepherds, fathers and sons, weddings and banquets, debts and servants. Their familiarity made them memorable, their imagery made them powerful, and their open-endedness invited reflection. Many ended without explicit application, forcing listeners to draw conclusions themselves.

This study examines Jesus'' major parables, exploring their original contexts, intended meanings, and applications for today. We''ll see the parables'' common themes: the nature of God''s kingdom, the character of God, the response God seeks, and the judgment awaiting those who reject Him. These stories, told 2,000 years ago, still have power to convict, comfort, and transform.'
WHERE slug = 'parables-of-jesus-21';

-- Standing Firm Under Pressure
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Pressure comes in many forms: persecution for faith, temptation to compromise, cultural opposition to biblical values, suffering that tests resolve. The Bible assumes believers will face pressure and provides resources for standing firm rather than caving in.

Daniel and his friends modeled standing firm in Babylon—refusing the king''s food, refusing to bow to the idol, continuing to pray despite the decree. They weren''t confrontational for its own sake, but they wouldn''t compromise on non-negotiables. Significantly, they trusted God with outcomes while remaining faithful to convictions.

The New Testament likewise prepares believers for pressure: "Everyone who wants to live a godly life in Christ Jesus will be persecuted" (2 Timothy 3:12). Yet it also provides resources: the Spirit''s power, the armor of God, the community of believers, and the hope of ultimate vindication. This study equips you to stand firm when pressure mounts, drawing strength from those who stood firm before you.'
WHERE slug = 'standing-firm-pressure';

-- Spiritual Warfare and Strength
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Spiritual warfare isn''t superstition or metaphor—it''s reality. The Bible presents a cosmic conflict between God and Satan, with earth as the battleground and human souls as the prize. Paul wrote, "Our struggle is not against flesh and blood, but against... the spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly realms" (Ephesians 6:12).

Yet the enemy is already defeated. Jesus'' death and resurrection "disarmed the powers and authorities... triumphing over them by the cross" (Colossians 2:15). Satan is a conquered foe, though still active. Our warfare is not to win victory but to enforce the victory Christ already won.

This study examines spiritual warfare biblically: Satan''s tactics (deception, accusation, temptation), our defenses (truth, righteousness, faith, salvation, the Word, prayer), and victory''s basis (Christ''s finished work). We''ll avoid two errors: ignoring the spiritual dimension of life''s struggles, and seeing demons behind every difficulty. The goal is sober awareness and confident standing in Christ''s victory.'
WHERE slug = 'spiritual-warfare-strength';

-- Serving Like Jesus
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus redefined greatness: "Whoever wants to become great among you must be your servant, and whoever wants to be first must be slave of all. For even the Son of Man did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many" (Mark 10:43-45).

The night before His death, Jesus wrapped a towel around His waist and washed His disciples'' feet—the job of the lowest servant. Peter protested, but Jesus insisted: "I have set you an example that you should do as I have done for you" (John 13:15). The Creator of the universe knelt before sinful men with a basin and towel.

This study examines Jesus'' servant heart and its implications for us. We''ll explore serving in various contexts: home, church, workplace, and community. We''ll address obstacles to serving: pride, busyness, fear of inadequacy, and desire for recognition. The goal is developing Jesus'' mindset—considering others better than ourselves and looking to their interests, not only our own (Philippians 2:3-4).'
WHERE slug = 'serving-like-jesus';

-- Renewing Your Mind
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Romans 12:2 commands: "Do not conform to the pattern of this world, but be transformed by the renewing of your mind." Transformation happens not through willpower but through changed thinking. What we believe shapes how we behave. Wrong beliefs produce wrong living; right beliefs produce right living.

The mind is a battlefield. Paul wrote about "demolishing arguments and every pretension that sets itself up against the knowledge of God" and "taking captive every thought to make it obedient to Christ" (2 Corinthians 10:5). Our thoughts need examination, filtering, and often replacement with truth.

This study explores mind renewal: identifying lies we believe (about God, ourselves, others, circumstances), replacing them with scriptural truth, and developing thought patterns that align with reality. Practical disciplines include Scripture meditation, memorization, and self-talk correction. The goal isn''t positive thinking but true thinking—aligning our minds with how things actually are in God''s economy.'
WHERE slug = 'renewing-your-mind';

-- Discovering Your Purpose
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The search for purpose is universal. "Why am I here? What am I supposed to do with my life?" These questions reflect God-given longings to matter, to contribute, to leave the world better than we found it. Scripture provides answers that transcend the world''s empty alternatives.

The Bible reveals both universal and particular purposes. Every human exists to glorify God and enjoy Him forever (Westminster Catechism). Every believer is called to grow in Christ, serve the church, and reach the lost. Within these broad purposes, God has specific plans for each person—the "good works, which God prepared in advance for us to do" (Ephesians 2:10).

This study explores biblical purpose: the general calling all believers share, the specific calling that varies by person, and how to discern God''s direction for your life. We''ll examine how passions, abilities, experiences, and circumstances point toward purpose. The goal is clarity about why you''re here and confidence to pursue God''s design for your unique life.'
WHERE slug = 'discovering-purpose';

-- God''s Love 14 Days
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = '"God is love" (1 John 4:8). This is not merely one of God''s attributes but His essential nature. Everything God does flows from love: creation, redemption, discipline, and final judgment. Understanding God''s love transforms how we view Him, ourselves, and others.

Divine love differs from human love in crucial ways. It''s unconditional—not based on the beloved''s worthiness. It''s initiating—God loved us first. It''s sacrificial—demonstrated supremely at the cross. It''s eternal—nothing can separate us from it. Human love responds to attractiveness; divine love creates worth in its objects.

This study explores God''s love through Scripture: how it''s revealed in His actions, how it''s experienced personally, and how it transforms our relationships with others. We''ll address questions like: If God loves me, why does He allow suffering? Can I lose God''s love? How does understanding His love change daily living? The goal is moving from knowing about God''s love to being rooted and established in it (Ephesians 3:17-19).'
WHERE slug = 'gods-love-14';

-- God''s Will for Your Life
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Few questions cause more anxiety than "What is God''s will for my life?" Christians agonize over decisions, fearing they''ll miss God''s plan and end up in His "second best." But this anxiety often stems from a misunderstanding of how God guides.

Scripture distinguishes between God''s sovereign will (His ultimate plan that always happens), His moral will (commands He reveals in Scripture), and His individual will (specific direction for particular decisions). The first two are certain; the third is where we often struggle.

The good news: much of God''s will is already revealed. "It is God''s will that you should be sanctified" (1 Thessalonians 4:3). "Give thanks in all circumstances; for this is God''s will for you" (1 Thessalonians 5:18). When we''re walking in these revealed commands, we can trust that God guides our steps even when we don''t hear a specific voice. This study explores biblical guidance, providing freedom from the paralysis of waiting for a sign.'
WHERE slug = 'gods-will-for-life';

-- Heaven, Hell, and Eternity
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Eternity is real. What happens after death isn''t endless speculation—God has revealed it in Scripture. Heaven and hell are actual destinations where people consciously exist forever. These truths should shape how we live now and motivate us to reach others.

Heaven is more than clouds and harps. It''s the presence of God, the joy of Christ, the fellowship of the redeemed, and eventually a renewed creation (new heaven and new earth) where God dwells with His people. There will be no tears, death, mourning, crying, or pain (Revelation 21:4). It''s the home we''ve longed for without knowing it.

Hell is equally real—eternal separation from God and everything good. Jesus spoke more about hell than anyone else in Scripture, warning of outer darkness, weeping and gnashing of teeth, unquenchable fire. These aren''t scare tactics but loving warnings from One who died to save us from this fate. This study examines what Scripture teaches about eternity, answering common questions and applying these truths to life and mission.'
WHERE slug = 'heaven-hell-eternity';

-- Peace Beyond Understanding
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Paul promised a peace "which transcends all understanding" that will "guard your hearts and minds in Christ Jesus" (Philippians 4:7). This isn''t positive thinking or denial—it''s supernatural peace that makes no sense given circumstances. And it''s available to every believer.

Peace in Scripture (shalom) is more than absence of conflict. It''s wholeness, flourishing, things as they should be. Jesus told His disciples, "Peace I leave with you; my peace I give you. I do not give to you as the world gives" (John 14:27). His peace exists independent of circumstances because it''s rooted in relationship with Him.

This study explores biblical peace: its source (reconciliation with God), its scope (internal, relational, and ultimate), and its practice (specific actions that cultivate peace). We''ll examine how Jesus remained peaceful amid chaos, how early Christians faced martyrdom with serenity, and how we can experience supernatural peace today. The anxious world desperately needs people who radiate this peace.'
WHERE slug = 'peace-beyond-understanding';

-- Pray Like Jesus
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Jesus prayed. The eternal Son of God, through whom all things were created, regularly withdrew to pray. If He needed to pray, how much more do we? His prayer life reveals priorities, patterns, and principles that can transform our own communication with the Father.

The Gospels record Jesus praying at His baptism, before choosing the twelve, before Peter''s confession, at the transfiguration, for children brought to Him, at Lazarus''s tomb, for Peter''s faith, in Gethsemane, and from the cross. Luke particularly emphasizes Jesus'' prayer life, showing Him withdrawing to lonely places to pray (Luke 5:16).

This study examines Jesus'' prayers, especially the Lord''s Prayer (His model for disciples) and His High Priestly Prayer (John 17). We''ll learn how Jesus addressed the Father, what He prayed for, and how He combined active ministry with regular withdrawal for prayer. The goal is developing a prayer life shaped by Jesus'' example—not religious duty but relational intimacy with our Father.'
WHERE slug = 'pray-like-jesus';

-- Promises for Hard Times
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'The Bible contains thousands of promises—divine commitments that God stakes His character on. When circumstances shake us, these promises provide solid ground. They don''t deny reality but anchor us in a greater reality: God''s faithfulness and sovereignty.

Some promises are conditional (requiring our obedience); others are unconditional. Some are for specific people at specific times; others are for all believers in all ages. This study focuses on promises with broad application—assurances every believer can claim regardless of situation.

Each day presents a cluster of promises around a theme: God''s presence, provision, protection, peace, power, and more. The goal isn''t just knowing these promises but internalizing them—hiding them in your heart for moments when you need them most. Many believers have found that promises memorized in seasons of calm become lifelines in seasons of crisis. This study builds your personal collection.'
WHERE slug = 'promises-when-hard';

-- Promise of Eternal Life
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = '"For God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son, that whoever believes in him shall not perish but have eternal life" (John 3:16). Eternal life is Christianity''s ultimate promise—not just endless existence but a quality of life that begins now and continues forever.

Jesus defined eternal life as knowing "the only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom you have sent" (John 17:3). It''s relational, not merely durational. It''s present, not merely future. Believers have already "crossed over from death to life" (John 5:24). We experience eternal life now in preview; we''ll experience it fully when Christ returns.

This study explores eternal life: what it is, how we receive it, how we know we have it, and what it means for daily living. We''ll address questions: Can eternal life be lost? What happens immediately after death? What will the resurrection body be like? What will we do in eternity? The goal is both assurance and anticipation—confident hope that transforms present living.'
WHERE slug = 'promise-eternal-life';

-- Scripture Memory Challenge
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Memorizing Scripture is an ancient practice with powerful benefits. The psalmist wrote, "I have hidden your word in my heart that I might not sin against you" (Psalm 119:11). Stored Scripture provides resources for temptation, tools for spiritual warfare, and treasures for meditation.

Some think memory work is just for children, but memorization actually gets easier with practice regardless of age. The key is systematic approach: choose meaningful verses, break them into phrases, review regularly, and apply what you learn. The goal isn''t impressive recitation but deep internalization.

This study guides you through memorizing key verses while teaching memorization techniques. We''ll cover foundational verses about salvation, identity in Christ, spiritual warfare, and practical living. By the end, you''ll have a core collection of memorized Scripture and skills to continue adding more. These hidden treasures will emerge in moments of need—the Spirit bringing to remembrance what you''ve stored in your heart.'
WHERE slug = 'scripture-memory-challenge';

-- Sin, Repentance, and Redemption
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Sin is Christianity''s uncomfortable topic—but the gospel only makes sense against its backdrop. Sin is the disease; Christ is the cure. Minimizing sin diminishes the cross. Understanding sin deeply leads to appreciating grace more fully.

The Bible uses multiple words for sin: missing the mark, transgression, iniquity, lawlessness. Sin is fundamentally rebellion against God—declaring independence from His rule and rejecting His right to define good and evil. Its consequences are devastating: guilt, shame, broken relationships, spiritual death, and eternal separation from God.

Repentance is God''s solution for sin in believers'' lives. It means changing your mind (the word''s literal meaning), which leads to changing your direction. True repentance involves confession, renunciation, and turning toward God. Redemption is God''s provision—Christ paying the price to free us from sin''s penalty and power. This study traces the biblical story of sin, repentance, and redemption, applying these truths to daily experience of confession and renewal.'
WHERE slug = 'sin-repentance-redemption';

-- Solomon - Wisdom and Warning
UPDATE public.reading_plans
SET day1_context = 'Solomon is the Bible''s paradox: the wisest man who lived also made catastrophically foolish choices. His life demonstrates that knowledge alone doesn''t guarantee wise living—wisdom must be applied, and even the gifted can fall when they fail to follow their own counsel.

Solomon began brilliantly. When God offered him anything, he asked for wisdom to govern. God granted wisdom plus wealth and honor unasked (1 Kings 3:12-13). He built the magnificent temple, wrote proverbs and songs, and attracted dignitaries from distant lands, including the Queen of Sheba who declared, "The half was not told me" (1 Kings 10:7).

Yet Solomon married 700 wives and 300 concubines (explicitly forbidden for kings in Deuteronomy 17:17). These foreign wives "turned his heart after other gods" (1 Kings 11:4). The wisest man built shrines to pagan deities. His excessive taxation laid the groundwork for kingdom division. Solomon warns us: finish well. This study examines both his wisdom and his warning.'
WHERE slug = 'solomon-wisdom-warning';
